  "text": "The general theory of the second best, upon which [CITATION_1] reflects after 50 years, uses demonstrative reasoning to demonstrate the general impossibility of Pareto improvements through piecemeal policy guided by the necessary conditions for Pareto efficiency. While this theory works against the offering of simple policy measures, it also opens into a vast expanse of hypothetical policy measures that feature an expansion in the violations of the conditions for competitive equilibrium as a means for pursuing Pareto efficiency in a second-best world. If reality conforms to all but one condition for Pareto efficiency, removal of the one impediment will be a clear improvement. But if two or more margins of imperfection exist, removing one imperfection can't be demonstrated to be a Pareto-efficient move. Where much policy analysis councils removal of what are claimed to be margins of imperfection, second-best theory can countenance the addition of further imperfections as a corrective movement.",
